qas.question: How has Switzerland maintained its relationships with the EU?
In recent years, what have the Swiss brought their economic practices into conformity with?
What have the Swiss tried to enhance by conforming to EU economic practices?
How much did the Swiss economy grow in 2010?
Which conservative party is popularly against joining the EU?

context: Switzerland voted against membership in the European Economic Area in a referendum in December 1992 and has since maintained and developed its relationships with the European Union (EU) and European countries <a0_0>through bilateral agreements<a0_0/>. In March 2001, the Swiss people refused in a popular vote to start accession negotiations with <a1_0>the EU<a1_0/>. In recent years, the Swiss have brought their economic practices largely into conformity with those of the EU in many ways, in an effort to enhance their <a2_0>international competitiveness<a2_0/>. The economy grew at <a3_0>3%<a3_0/> in 2010, 1.9% in 2011, and 1% in 2012. Full EU membership is a long-term objective of some in the Swiss government, but there is considerable popular sentiment against this supported by the conservative <a4_0>SVP party<a4_0/>. The western French-speaking areas and the urban regions of the rest of the country tend to be more pro-EU, however with far from any significant share of the population.
